import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
In[10]:
airbnb = pd.read_csv("Data/processed-data/nyc-airbnb-listings-2024-cleaned.csv")

# airbnb.head()
In[11]:
nyc_palette = {
    "Bronx": "#A73535",  
    "Brooklyn": "#B5A21F", 
    "Manhattan": "#2E8B57", 
    "Queens": "#1C4E80",       
    "Staten Island": "#6B6B6B" 
}

plt.figure(figsize = (10,6))

# Price distribution per borough
sns.boxplot(x="neighbourhood_group", y="price", data=airbnb, showfliers=False, hue="neighbourhood_group", legend=False, palette=nyc_palette)

plt.xlabel("Borough")
plt.ylabel("Price ($)")
plt.title("Price Distribution per Borough (Without Outliers)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

plt.show()

This boxplot visualizes the distribution of Airbnb prices per Borough. At first glance, the median price seems to decrease as we move from Manhattan to Staten Island. This makes sense, especially in current times. Manhattan is a borough that attracts affluent people, while Brooklyn has mid-range pricing, appealing more to younger and budget-conscious guests. On the contrary, Staten Island and the Bronx seem to offer more budget-friendly options.

These insights can help hosts strategize on where to set up new listings based on the price trends and the type of crowd they want to appeal to. Hosts looking to attract high-end clientele may consider Manhattan, while those aiming for a more diverse and budget-conscious audience might opt for Brooklyn, Staten Island, or the Bronx.

In[12]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

# Create scatter plot with improved aesthetics
sns.scatterplot(
    x="availability_365", 
    y="price", 
    data=airbnb, 
    alpha=0.3, 
    color="#FF8C00",  # Dark orange for better visibility
    edgecolor="black"  # Black edge color for better distinction
)

# Add labels and title with improved formatting
plt.xlabel("Availability (Days per Year)", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Price ($)", fontsize=12, fontweight="bold")
plt.title("Scatter Plot: Availability vs. Price", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")

# Improve grid visibility for better readability
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.5)

# Show plot
plt.show()

This scatter plot visualizes the relationship between Airbnb listing prices and availability. At first glance, the points appear widely dispersed, potentially implying that price does not significantly impact availability. One possible explanation for this lack of correlation could be the variation in hosting strategies. Some hosts may list their properties year-round (365 days), while others might operate seasonally as part-time hosts. This diversity in hosting approaches could contribute to the scattered distribution of data points, obscuring any direct relationship between price and availability.

In[13]:
custom_palette = ["#2E8B57", "#1C4E80", "#6B6B6B", "#FFD700", "#A73535",
                       "#D35400", "#E67E22", "#8E44AD", "#3498DB", "#FF5733"]

# Choosing hosts with the most listings and include host names
top_hosts = airbnb.groupby(["host_id", "host_name"])["id"].count().reset_index().rename(columns={"id": "listing_count"})
top_hosts = top_hosts.sort_values(by="listing_count", ascending=False).head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x="listing_count", y="host_name", data=top_hosts, hue="host_name", palette=custom_palette, legend=False)

plt.xlabel("Number of Listings")
plt.ylabel("Host Name")
plt.title("Top 10 Hosts with the Most Listings")

plt.show()

This bar chart showcases the top 10 Airbnb hosts in New York City based on the number of listings they manage. The top two names, "Blueground" and "Eugene," suggest that these are commercial-scale hosts rather than individual property owners renting out personal spaces. Notably, there is a significant disparity between the number of listings managed by the top two hosts compared to the others in the top 10. This observation could indicate that the NYC Airbnb market is dominated by a small number of large-scale players. The dominance of a few hosts in the market might suggest that operating a large-scale Airbnb business in NYC could be a lucrative venture.

In[14]:
# Computing correlation matrix for numerical features
correlation_matrix = airbnb[['price', 'minimum_nights', 'availability_365', 'number_of_reviews', 'reviews_per_month']].corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(
    correlation_matrix, 
    annot=True, 
    cmap="coolwarm",  
    fmt=".2f", 
    linewidths=0.8,  
    square=True, 
    cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.8, "aspect": 30},  
    annot_kws={"fontsize": 10}  
)

plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Airbnb Features")
plt.show()

This is a heatmap of the correlation coefficient between the different numerical Airbnb features. Notably, the number_of_reviews has a strong positive correlation of 0.63 with reviews_per_month. This suggests that listings receiving more reviews overall also tend to receive more reviews on a monthly basis. Conversely, minimum_nights and reviews_per_month exhibit a strong negative correlation of -0.33. This indicates that listings with higher minimum-night stay requirements are likely to receive fewer reviews per month. Longer minimum stays may lead to fewer bookings and, consequently, fewer opportunities for guests to leave reviews. Interestingly, the price feature has very weak correlations with 'minimum_nights', 'available_365', 'number_of_reviews', and 'reviews_per_month'. This observation implies that price alone does not significantly influence the frequency of reviews for a listing.

import folium
from folium.plugins import HeatMap

# Map is centered around NY
nyc_map = folium.Map(location=[40.7128, -74.0060], zoom_start=8)

heat_data = list(zip(airbnb['latitude'], airbnb['longitude'], airbnb['price']))
HeatMap(heat_data, radius=12, blur=8, max_zoom=13).add_to(nyc_map)

nyc_map

This interactive heatmap illustrates the density of Airbnb listings across New York City. The orange to red zones indicate areas with a high concentration of listings, while the green to blue zones represent areas with fewer listings as you move further away from the city center. This pattern is consistent with Manhattan being widely known for its businesses, tourism, and luxury accommodations, whereas Brooklyn and Queens are primarily residential areas. Beyond simply showing that Manhattan is densely populated with Airbnb listings, this heatmap also highlights areas in the outer boroughs that could have potential for growth in the Airbnb market.
